1
00:00:38,065 --> 00:00:39,686
It’s the Christmas season,

2
00:00:40,202 --> 00:00:43,065
a time for telling colourful
holiday stories.

3
00:00:43,725 --> 00:00:46,660
My favourite story of all time
is about my grandma.

4
00:00:47,529 --> 00:00:50,183
She had this encounter with a reindeer.

5
00:00:53,485 --> 00:00:56,673
Grandma got run over by a reindeer

6
00:00:57,795 --> 00:01:00,828
walking home from our house Christmas Eve.

7
00:01:02,270 --> 00:01:05,317
You can say there’s no such thing
as Santa,

8
00:01:06,446 --> 00:01:09,605
but as for me and grandpa, we believe.

9
00:01:10,760 --> 00:01:13,245
Grandma got run over by a reindeer,
all right?

10
00:01:13,776 --> 00:01:18,055
And as incredible as it was,
it almost put an end to Christmas.

11
00:01:18,439 --> 00:01:20,945
But I’m getting ahead of myself.

12
00:01:20,953 --> 00:01:23,281
So let’s go back to the beginning.

13
00:01:26,194 --> 00:01:31,422
It was December and everyone in Cityville
was caught up in the chaos of the holidays.

14
00:01:32,205 --> 00:01:35,078
And no place was busier
than my grandma’s store.

15
00:01:36,710 --> 00:01:38,102
My grandma’s store!

16
00:01:40,345 --> 00:01:41,564
There it is.

17
00:01:41,655 --> 00:01:44,677
Check it out.
It was a one-of-a-kind place.

18
00:01:44,733 --> 00:01:47,220
She carried all kinds of stuff
year around.

19
00:01:48,198 --> 00:01:50,672
She sold decorations, handmade toys –

20
00:01:50,980 --> 00:01:54,146
at least one of anything you could
imagine for the holidays.

21
00:01:55,447 --> 00:01:56,645
There’s grandma.

22
00:01:56,864 --> 00:02:00,688
Did I mention she likes to dress up
to read Christmas stories to kids

23
00:02:01,038 --> 00:02:02,648
while their parents shop?

24
00:02:03,835 --> 00:02:08,334
“And the little baby Christmas tree
looked up at papa tree…” – Grandma!

25
00:02:09,058 --> 00:02:11,444
And that’s me, Jake Spankenheimer.

26
00:02:11,551 --> 00:02:14,020
Cousin Mel is scaring away
another customer!

27
00:02:14,193 --> 00:02:17,740
You can stop right there.
That’s shoplifting, missy.

28
00:02:18,066 --> 00:02:20,924
Now, what seems to be the problem?

29
00:02:21,117 --> 00:02:23,169
Problem? No problem.

30
00:02:23,520 --> 00:02:25,459
No money, no merchandise.

31
00:02:25,768 --> 00:02:26,581
No way!

32
00:02:27,230 --> 00:02:29,587
Your credit is always good here, Martha.

33
00:02:29,778 --> 00:02:32,991
Why, you just stop by
when you get your next paycheck.

34
00:02:33,188 --> 00:02:36,001
Thanks, grandma.
Everyone have a merry Christmas!

35
00:02:36,432 --> 00:02:37,332
You, too.

36
00:02:38,449 --> 00:02:40,066
Things have to change.

37
00:02:40,384 --> 00:02:44,115
This store can’t get rich selling
holiday pastries on credit.

38
00:02:44,876 --> 00:02:48,598
You’re not a businesswoman.
You’re an old fruitcake.

39
00:02:50,371 --> 00:02:53,908
Everyone else is happy the way things are.
Right, Frank?

40
00:02:54,004 --> 00:02:56,037
Beats punching a time clock
for someone else.

41
00:02:56,038 --> 00:02:58,542
I like spending time with the family at work.

42
00:02:58,630 --> 00:03:00,289
You see, look around you.

43
00:03:00,524 --> 00:03:01,870
We <i>are</i> rich.

44
00:03:02,137 --> 00:03:04,313
Life’s about being nice to people.

45
00:03:04,682 --> 00:03:05,839
Money – ah!

46
00:03:06,387 --> 00:03:07,895
I’d say we make enough.

47
00:03:08,072 --> 00:03:08,896
Enough?

48
00:03:09,494 --> 00:03:11,341
Enough is never enough!

49
00:03:19,413 --> 00:03:22,409
A set of replacement wheels
for my rollerblades…

50
00:03:22,858 --> 00:03:24,773
Adding to your Christmas wish list?

51
00:03:25,263 --> 00:03:26,639
Sisters!

52
00:03:26,945 --> 00:03:28,651
Ah, yeah, I thought so.

53
00:03:28,735 --> 00:03:31,773
A computer nerd who still
believes in Santa Claus.

54
00:03:31,831 --> 00:03:33,983
You’re so reality challenged.

55
00:03:35,561 --> 00:03:38,342
Daphne, stop teasing your brother!

56
00:03:38,657 --> 00:03:40,074
He started it!

57
00:03:42,612 --> 00:03:45,665
Come on downstairs.
Your dad has a surprise.

58
00:03:47,106 --> 00:03:48,232
Tell her, mom.

59
00:03:48,303 --> 00:03:49,826
Santa Claus <i>is</i> real.

60
00:03:49,891 --> 00:03:50,609
Well,

61
00:03:51,098 --> 00:03:52,861
there’s no easy answer.

62
00:03:53,333 --> 00:03:55,597
Historically, there was a saint Nick who

63
00:03:55,790 --> 00:03:59,923
with a loving heart filled children’s
shoes with gifts of all sorts.

64
00:04:00,174 --> 00:04:04,180
So, Santa today represents
the true meaning of Christmas –

65
00:04:04,318 --> 00:04:05,576
giving to others.

66
00:04:09,912 --> 00:04:11,977
Dad, is Santa Claus real?

67
00:04:14,367 --> 00:04:15,543
What your mother said.

68
00:04:16,448 --> 00:04:17,935
Hey, who wants to put up a tree?

69
00:04:18,209 --> 00:04:19,917
Oh, right, Christmas tree!

70
00:04:22,727 --> 00:04:24,451
That’s not a Christmas tree.

71
00:04:24,861 --> 00:04:27,732
You’re looking at the new inflatable
Christmas tree manufactured

72
00:04:27,752 --> 00:04:29,987
by the Cityville Own-all Corporation.

73
00:04:30,405 --> 00:04:33,875
But our family always goes out
and gets a real tree.

74
00:04:34,421 --> 00:04:36,532
Don’t you want to save the forest?

75
00:04:37,106 --> 00:04:38,944
Nobody gets a tree anymore.

76
00:04:39,143 --> 00:04:40,256
It’s not cool.

77
00:04:50,848 --> 00:04:54,363
Wish they had Christmas trees
like that when I was a boy.

78
00:04:55,043 --> 00:04:57,309
Here we go again.

79
00:04:57,530 --> 00:05:00,114
We had to chop our trees down by hand.

80
00:05:00,369 --> 00:05:04,314
Never forget the time I had to use
a beaver for a chain saw.

81
00:05:05,593 --> 00:05:07,971
Last time you told it,
it was a woodpecker.

82
00:05:08,082 --> 00:05:10,289
Okay, everyone, gather ’round your dad.

83
00:05:10,564 --> 00:05:13,641
I want a video of our first
inflatable tree.

84
00:05:14,244 --> 00:05:16,502
This tree is going to save lots of time.

85
00:05:16,796 --> 00:05:18,303
What’s the fun in that?

86
00:05:19,546 --> 00:05:22,094
Where’s the jabbing yourself
with pine needles,

87
00:05:22,175 --> 00:05:27,448
hanging ornaments, the old-fashioned
smell of a genuine douglas fir?

88
00:05:28,230 --> 00:05:31,536
If you like old-fashioned smells
I’ll get my fishing boots.

89
00:05:36,122 --> 00:05:36,863
Oops…

90
00:05:37,345 --> 00:05:38,134
Sorry.

91
00:05:43,862 --> 00:05:45,767
As crazy as things were at home,

92
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:50,092
they got crazier the day I met
the most powerful man in Cityville.

93
00:05:51,402 --> 00:05:54,218
– Excuse me. I’m…
– Austin Bucks!

94
00:05:54,585 --> 00:05:58,295
CEO of the Cityville Own-all Corporation.

95
00:05:58,981 --> 00:06:01,072
Grandma says you own everything.

96
00:06:01,360 --> 00:06:04,597
Well, not yet, but that’s why
I want to speak to your grandma.

97
00:06:04,975 --> 00:06:06,659
I’m sure she wants to see you.

98
00:06:07,097 --> 00:06:12,000
But right now, grandma Elfen-heimer
is reading to the kids.

99
00:06:12,336 --> 00:06:13,627
I heard about that.

100
00:06:13,645 --> 00:06:17,173
Say, you wouldn’t happen to have
an extra elf costume I could wear?

101
00:06:17,359 --> 00:06:20,084
Nope, sorry. But there’s a troll costume.

102
00:06:24,932 --> 00:06:27,636
Well, grandma Elfenheimer.

103
00:06:27,683 --> 00:06:30,133
Mr. Austin “Troll” Bucks.

104
00:06:30,628 --> 00:06:33,857
I don’t suppose you’re dressed that way
to read “Billy Goats Gruff” to the kids.

105
00:06:33,893 --> 00:06:37,522
No. I did it so you’d listen
to my offer to buy your store.

106
00:06:37,585 --> 00:06:39,348
Didn’t help. Don’t want to listen.

107
00:06:39,380 --> 00:06:41,068
I’ll pay a lot of money.

108
00:06:41,435 --> 00:06:42,697
Ka-ching!

109
00:06:43,186 --> 00:06:45,962
You’d be selling to the biggest
and the best.

110
00:06:46,060 --> 00:06:49,527
Do you know why my company controls
every mall and sidewalk, Santa?

111
00:06:49,846 --> 00:06:53,055
Because people are too busy
to think about Christmas.

112
00:06:53,077 --> 00:06:55,890
With their cellular phones
and fax machines, e-mail

113
00:06:56,199 --> 00:06:57,992
they’re never really away from work.

114
00:06:58,040 --> 00:06:59,870
And you figure you’re helping.

115
00:06:59,969 --> 00:07:03,324
Yes. There wouldn’t be a Cityville
Christmas without me.

116
00:07:03,746 --> 00:07:08,105
Your store sits on the perfect place
to build the crown jewel of my empire.

117
00:07:08,311 --> 00:07:13,644
Picture it: Gifts delivered on
Christmas Eve by our new sleighmobile.

118
00:07:15,375 --> 00:07:17,059
Isn’t that what Santa does?

119
00:07:17,355 --> 00:07:20,562
How cute. He still believes in
Santa Claus.

120
00:07:20,726 --> 00:07:23,678
Jake, do you think
I should sell the store?

121
00:07:23,916 --> 00:07:25,167
Are you kidding?

122
00:07:25,279 --> 00:07:26,721
I love this place.

123
00:07:27,321 --> 00:07:30,806
You with no store would be like
Christmas without Santa.

124
00:07:31,069 --> 00:07:33,851
Well, there you have it –
from the mouths of babes.

125
00:07:35,244 --> 00:07:39,116
Surely you’re not going to let Jake
make such a big decision.

126
00:07:39,393 --> 00:07:40,604
He’s just a kid.

127
00:07:41,840 --> 00:07:44,136
In case you change your mind.

128
00:07:44,543 --> 00:07:45,640
Thank you.

129
00:07:46,017 --> 00:07:48,454
And you can keep the troll costume.

130
00:07:49,269 --> 00:07:50,354
Bye-bye.

131
00:07:51,414 --> 00:07:53,896
I’ve always loved a man in tights.

132
00:07:57,660 --> 00:08:00,169
Grandma, do you realize
what you just did?

133
00:08:00,204 --> 00:08:02,615
You let my fortune walk out the door!

134
00:08:02,690 --> 00:08:04,453
That was my future!

135
00:08:05,009 --> 00:08:07,483
I mean Jake’s future –

136
00:08:07,803 --> 00:08:12,268
Money for college, travel to Italy,
world cruises, sports cars, jewels…

137
00:08:13,483 --> 00:08:16,962
I’d tell you to put a cork in it,
you greedy money-grubber!

138
00:08:17,181 --> 00:08:19,296
But grandmas shouldn’t talk that way.

139
00:08:19,398 --> 00:08:20,249
Grandma,

140
00:08:20,466 --> 00:08:22,123
if this store were mine,

141
00:08:22,202 --> 00:08:24,350
I’d sell it.

142
00:08:24,573 --> 00:08:27,812
Cousin Mel,
this store will never be yours.

143
00:08:28,642 --> 00:08:29,540
Oh, yeah!

144
00:08:36,289 --> 00:08:38,084
We’ll see.

145
00:08:40,179 --> 00:08:41,607
Cousin Mel was wrong.

146
00:08:41,839 --> 00:08:44,867
You can keep a store going
on goodwill and baked goods.

147
00:08:45,372 --> 00:08:48,005
By the looks of my house
at Christmas time

148
00:08:48,115 --> 00:08:52,146
you’d think grandma was single-handedly
supplying the entire free world

149
00:08:52,150 --> 00:08:53,655
with Christmas goodies.

150
00:08:53,856 --> 00:08:57,192
The way I see it, you can divide
the world into two groups:

151
00:08:57,409 --> 00:09:00,509
People who like fruitcake,
and all the rest of us.

152
00:09:03,341 --> 00:09:07,944
The holidays were upon us
and things were going fine

153
00:09:08,222 --> 00:09:12,855
till the day I heard the doorbell
and a chill ran up my spine.

154
00:09:13,403 --> 00:09:17,594
I grabbed the wife and children
as the postman wheeled it in.

155
00:09:18,256 --> 00:09:22,456
My yearly Christmas nightmare
has just come back again:

156
00:09:22,653 --> 00:09:25,481
It was harder than the head
of uncle Bucky,

157
00:09:25,791 --> 00:09:28,067
heavy as a sermon of preacher Lucky,

158
00:09:28,225 --> 00:09:32,300
one’s enough to give the whole state
of Kentucky a great big bellyache.

159
00:09:32,579 --> 00:09:35,571
It was denser than a drove of
barnyard turkeys,

160
00:09:35,654 --> 00:09:38,006
tougher than a truckload of all-beef jerky

161
00:09:38,072 --> 00:09:40,432
drier than a drought in Albuquerque –

162
00:09:40,537 --> 00:09:42,480
grandma’s killer fruitcake.

163
00:09:43,541 --> 00:09:45,190
You’re a great helper, Jake.

164
00:09:45,210 --> 00:09:48,622
Now, just stir that bowl of ingredients
and it’s ready for the oven.

165
00:09:48,638 --> 00:09:52,272
Grandma, Jake,
I’m afraid Doofus got out again.

166
00:09:52,295 --> 00:09:54,335
I can’t find him anywhere.

167
00:09:54,656 --> 00:09:58,256
Why, I wonder where that adorable dog
could have run off to this time.

168
00:09:58,591 --> 00:09:59,704
Come on, Jake.

169
00:10:02,805 --> 00:10:05,821
Hah! I don’t know who buys your
cakes and cookies

170
00:10:05,822 --> 00:10:08,799
but this will for darn sure
make everyone sick.

171
00:10:09,288 --> 00:10:11,832
That ought to stop people
from shopping at the store

172
00:10:12,168 --> 00:10:17,034
and with no customers you’ll
have to sell, grandma!

173
00:10:17,433 --> 00:10:19,585
Doofus was right next to the fireplace.

174
00:10:20,587 --> 00:10:22,059
Must have missed him.

175
00:10:22,455 --> 00:10:24,755
What were you saying?
I’d have to sell?

176
00:10:25,241 --> 00:10:28,303
Oh, sell a lot, the way
these pastries taste.

177
00:10:36,369 --> 00:10:39,828
Careful, grandma. Don’t drink too much
eggnog without your medication.

178
00:10:40,891 --> 00:10:43,835
You’d think at my age you’d
outgrow an allergy to eggs.

179
00:10:44,332 --> 00:10:46,626
Now, where’d I put those pills?

180
00:10:50,160 --> 00:10:54,221
I’ve got some mistletoe and holly. Who’s
going to help me with the decorating?

181
00:10:54,331 --> 00:10:59,961
– Can’t. Have to call my boyfriend.
– Sorry, grandma, got to dash to the gym.
– Uh, I’d love to, but Frank…

182
00:11:00,151 --> 00:11:03,214
The game’s just starting on TV.
– I’ll help you, grandma.

183
00:11:03,352 --> 00:11:04,587
My little man.

184
00:11:05,311 --> 00:11:05,997
Thanks.

185
00:11:06,290 --> 00:11:08,701
Nobody understood me like grandma did.

186
00:11:09,148 --> 00:11:12,292
Christmas time was as important to her
as it was to me.

187
00:11:18,477 --> 00:11:19,708
Well, we did it.

188
00:11:19,743 --> 00:11:21,663
That’s right on the nose, Jake.

189
00:11:22,005 --> 00:11:23,007
<i>We</i> did it.

190
00:11:25,522 --> 00:11:28,960
The sooner you go to sleep,
he sooner Santa will come.

191
00:11:29,434 --> 00:11:32,895
Grandma, Daphne says
here’s no such thing as Santa.

192
00:11:33,177 --> 00:11:35,783
Well, that’s because she
doesn’t believe like I do.

193
00:11:35,810 --> 00:11:37,248
Have you ever seen him?

194
00:11:37,274 --> 00:11:43,139
No, but I’ve seen him in the smiles of people
who share with others every Christmas.

195
00:11:44,502 --> 00:11:47,865
If you ever run into him, say hi for me.

196
00:11:51,957 --> 00:11:53,207
Good night, Jake.

197
00:11:57,494 --> 00:12:00,667
Grandma got run over by a reindeer

198
00:12:01,861 --> 00:12:04,863
walking home from our house
Christmas Eve.

199
00:12:06,291 --> 00:12:09,261
You can say there’s no such thing
as Santa,

200
00:12:10,456 --> 00:12:13,433
but as for me and grandpa, we believe.

201
00:12:13,486 --> 00:12:16,553
Well, I’m fixing to take these
extra cookies and cakes

202
00:12:16,565 --> 00:12:19,885
to the volunteers at the Cityville
community services building.

203
00:12:19,962 --> 00:12:21,993
It’s too late to go out now, grandma.

204
00:12:22,044 --> 00:12:25,159
If I’d had some help I would have been
finished hours ago.

205
00:12:25,413 --> 00:12:28,713
– I was busy.
– Sorry, had to finish my homework.
– Last-minute shopping.

206
00:12:30,864 --> 00:12:33,038
You’ve been drinking too much eggnog.

207
00:12:34,836 --> 00:12:36,978
– Please, don’t go!
– We’re begging!

208
00:12:40,068 --> 00:12:42,149
Besides, I left my medication
at the store.

209
00:12:58,981 --> 00:13:01,788
On, Donner! On, Blitzen!

210
00:13:03,673 --> 00:13:05,790
It’s him! Santa Claus!

211
00:13:06,417 --> 00:13:07,565
He is real!

212
00:13:09,806 --> 00:13:11,569
Grandma, watch out!

213
00:13:28,684 --> 00:13:30,125
Come on, everyone!

214
00:13:30,911 --> 00:13:33,857
Hurry! Grandma got run over
by Santa’s reindeer!

215
00:13:34,327 --> 00:13:38,951
– Jake, close the door and get in here.
– Santa hit grandma! Grandma needs help!

216
00:13:39,255 --> 00:13:42,622
The only person who needs
help in this family is you.

217
00:13:43,047 --> 00:13:45,706
Now, Jake, calm down. Take a breath.

218
00:13:46,888 --> 00:13:49,400
Okay, Santa Claus was
flying low like this.

219
00:13:49,613 --> 00:13:53,572
And grandma was walking like this
and … is here, and …

220
00:13:53,751 --> 00:13:56,089
Now, honey, you must have had
a bad dream.

221
00:13:56,128 --> 00:14:00,189
In case you haven’t noticed, Frank, your
son suffers from a dreaded affliction.

222
00:14:00,428 --> 00:14:03,383
– What affliction?
– The Santa Claus is real syndrome.

223
00:14:03,752 --> 00:14:05,182
He’s got all the symptoms:

224
00:14:05,209 --> 00:14:09,036
Writing lists to Santa, checking them
twice, good behavior,

225
00:14:09,228 --> 00:14:12,802
falling asleep before midnight.
I figure he gets it from his grandma.

226
00:14:12,882 --> 00:14:15,409
You saw what happened, didn’t you,
grandpa?

227
00:14:18,302 --> 00:14:20,503
I’m sorry. Were you talking to me?

228
00:14:20,692 --> 00:14:24,818
I was too busy watching grandma get
run over by a reindeer-drawn sleigh.

229
00:14:25,259 --> 00:14:25,977
Yes!

230
00:14:26,237 --> 00:14:28,773
What a sight!
Sleigh come out of nowhere.

231
00:14:29,261 --> 00:14:32,763
Grandma takes a header into the
snowbank. Sleigh vanishes…

232
00:14:33,185 --> 00:14:35,514
like the ghost of Christmas past!

233
00:14:36,374 --> 00:14:40,877
And that’s what’s called an advanced
case of Santa Claus is real syndrome.

234
00:14:41,448 --> 00:14:43,012
Oh, honestly, grandpa.

235
00:14:43,156 --> 00:14:45,433
We’ve got to go help grandma!

236
00:14:49,338 --> 00:14:51,046
Nothing is out there.

237
00:14:51,679 --> 00:14:53,308
Frank, do something.

238
00:14:53,773 --> 00:14:57,281
Look, Jake, if I call the local shelter
and have grandma speak to you

239
00:14:57,703 --> 00:14:58,910
will you go to bed?

240
00:14:58,951 --> 00:15:00,293
But she won’t!

241
00:15:00,742 --> 00:15:01,815
I saw her!

242
00:15:02,092 --> 00:15:05,210
I told you Santa hit her with his sleigh!

243
00:15:05,512 --> 00:15:06,821
Call the police!

244
00:15:09,881 --> 00:15:11,582
That’s right, officer.
Missing.

245
00:15:12,540 --> 00:15:14,004
Hit by Santa’s sleigh.

246
00:15:15,385 --> 00:15:17,329
Yes, we’ve been drinking eggnog.

247
00:15:19,525 --> 00:15:21,892
They’ll be out first thing in the morning.

248
00:15:23,934 --> 00:15:25,847
And what did you see, young man?

249
00:15:26,178 --> 00:15:28,849
I saw grandma get run over by a reindeer.

250
00:15:29,306 --> 00:15:30,997
Here we go again.

251
00:15:31,273 --> 00:15:33,957
Sorry, son, impossible.
Right here in the manual.

252
00:15:33,971 --> 00:15:36,170
There’s no such thing as Santa Claus.

253
00:15:36,393 --> 00:15:37,277
Is, too.

254
00:15:38,079 --> 00:15:41,218
We got a code 12-25:
Santa Claus is real syndrome –

255
00:15:41,260 --> 00:15:43,205
family dispute.
– Come on!

256
00:15:43,315 --> 00:15:45,441
I’ll show you where she got run over.

257
00:15:47,807 --> 00:15:50,552
When we found her Christmas morning

258
00:15:52,346 --> 00:15:54,515
at the scene of the attack…
– See?

259
00:15:56,635 --> 00:15:59,471
… she had hoofprints on her forehead

260
00:16:00,053 --> 00:16:03,248
and incriminating Claus marks
on her back.

261
00:16:03,761 --> 00:16:07,079
Okay, we’ve got some reindeer hoofprints
and sleigh tread marks leading to a…

262
00:16:07,080 --> 00:16:08,207
Oh, yeah!

263
00:16:08,237 --> 00:16:11,777
What appears to be an impression of a
person in the snow, look there. But, uh…

264
00:16:11,805 --> 00:16:14,270
How do we know it’s grandma?
– Doofus knows!

265
00:16:19,985 --> 00:16:21,825
That’s one of grandma’s shoes.

266
00:16:22,917 --> 00:16:24,876
That’s her special Christmas mug.

267
00:16:26,710 --> 00:16:27,783
Her medicine.

268
00:16:29,420 --> 00:16:30,803
And her cookies and…

269
00:16:31,972 --> 00:16:33,278
her fruitcake!

270
00:16:40,538 --> 00:16:42,313
Officer Lyon, check this out.

271
00:16:42,404 --> 00:16:44,225
Ooh, what do you make of this?

272
00:16:44,473 --> 00:16:49,164
Offhand, I’d say that’s animal hair.
Reindeer, 15-hands high, 12-point buck.

273
00:16:49,405 --> 00:16:54,657
By the markings, a sleigh-puller. Powerful,
capable of flight, age unknown, one of a…

274
00:16:55,078 --> 00:16:56,563
But it’s just a guess.

275
00:16:56,928 --> 00:17:00,652
Okay, then. I’ll just put it down
as sleighicular hit-and-run.

276
00:17:00,939 --> 00:17:02,383
What’s the code for that?

277
00:17:02,438 --> 00:17:05,200
You should remember that one.
It’s a 12-24.

278
00:17:05,709 --> 00:17:07,935
Oh, right, 12-24.

279
00:17:08,494 --> 00:17:09,338
I get it.

280
00:17:09,346 --> 00:17:11,372
12-24: Day before Christmas.

281
00:17:11,392 --> 00:17:13,054
Just a minute, Sherlock.

282
00:17:13,094 --> 00:17:16,856
Before you put out an APB for a sleigh
driven by Santa Claus –

283
00:17:16,911 --> 00:17:19,842
who, may I remind you, does not exist –

284
00:17:19,917 --> 00:17:22,024
I’d like to know where grandma is.

285
00:17:22,345 --> 00:17:24,895
Good point. We can work
the Santa angle later.

286
00:17:25,343 --> 00:17:27,146
Better get looking for the old broad.

287
00:17:27,479 --> 00:17:29,825
We’ll need a photo of the missing person.

288
00:17:31,977 --> 00:17:35,326
That started the biggest grandma hunt
in Cityville history.

289
00:17:35,722 --> 00:17:38,586
The police searched every
nook and cranny for granny.

290
00:17:38,865 --> 00:17:41,599
Time passed, and police kept
looking and looking.

291
00:17:41,952 --> 00:17:43,175
Months went by.

292
00:17:43,427 --> 00:17:44,891
We looked and looked.

293
00:17:46,080 --> 00:17:49,376
I even got permission to put
grandma’s picture on milk cartons.

294
00:17:49,915 --> 00:17:53,335
Nothing helped, not even stories
on the local news channel.

295
00:17:54,027 --> 00:17:56,396
Grandma was nowhere to be found.

296
00:17:59,956 --> 00:18:04,144
Grandma’s Christmas gifts remained
unopened and people dressed in black.

297
00:18:06,044 --> 00:18:08,941
Grandpa tried to cope by playing cards
with cousin Mel.

298
00:18:10,801 --> 00:18:14,801
It wasn’t any better at the store,
either. Mom and dad tried their best.

299
00:18:15,049 --> 00:18:18,076
But without grandma,
customers stopped coming in.

300
00:18:22,111 --> 00:18:24,442
My office said you called
and wanted to see me.

301
00:18:24,825 --> 00:18:29,170
I wanted to apologize for the way
grandma treated you last year.

302
00:18:30,123 --> 00:18:32,957
Did anyone ever tell you’re very good
looking for a man with…

303
00:18:33,436 --> 00:18:34,813
… deep pockets?

304
00:18:39,003 --> 00:18:40,259
I was dusting.

305
00:18:40,586 --> 00:18:42,365
Well, go dust somewhere else!

306
00:18:42,612 --> 00:18:45,619
You can’t tell me what to do.
It’s grandma’s store.

307
00:18:49,034 --> 00:18:53,978
That reminds me, are you still interested
in buying this establishment?

308
00:18:54,043 --> 00:18:57,261
Well, it’s the ideal location for our
sleighmobile division.

309
00:18:57,384 --> 00:19:01,171
Good, because I know grandma
would want me to sell it.

310
00:19:01,236 --> 00:19:02,920
I have the deed right here.

311
00:19:04,901 --> 00:19:08,638
Unfortunately, your name’s not on the
deed, just grandma and grandpa’s.

312
00:19:08,704 --> 00:19:12,208
But if grandpa agrees,
then I could buy the store.

313
00:19:12,269 --> 00:19:16,501
I’m sure I can trick… I mean,
get grandpa to agree.

314
00:19:22,677 --> 00:19:25,445
You’ve been so depressed
since grandma disappeared.

315
00:19:25,851 --> 00:19:30,494
That’s why I had you bring me to my
favorite restaurant to cheer you up.

316
00:19:31,056 --> 00:19:32,518
I’ll cure your sorrow.

317
00:19:32,903 --> 00:19:36,641
We’ll spruce up the store, order
new merchandise, hire a baker.

318
00:19:36,682 --> 00:19:39,885
It’s right here in these papers.
All you have to do is sign.

319
00:19:40,384 --> 00:19:41,114
Sing?

320
00:19:41,421 --> 00:19:42,526
No, sign.

321
00:19:42,812 --> 00:19:43,601
Sure.

322
00:19:43,774 --> 00:19:44,926
So, sign.

323
00:19:45,611 --> 00:19:46,816
I’d rather sing.

324
00:19:51,901 --> 00:19:55,915
Grandma’s spending Christmas
with the superstars

325
00:19:55,935 --> 00:19:59,296
since that reindeer ran her down
that fateful night .

326
00:20:00,952 --> 00:20:05,025
Grandma’s hanging out
with all those late, great stars

327
00:20:05,042 --> 00:20:08,819
for the heavenliest Christmas of her life.

328
00:20:09,151 --> 00:20:13,171
She’s standing under the mistletoe
with Elvis.

329
00:20:13,766 --> 00:20:17,468
He’s been consoling her
because she’s missing gramps.

330
00:20:18,322 --> 00:20:22,786
Then Elvis offers her the keys
to a new Cadillac,

331
00:20:22,837 --> 00:20:26,527
well, well, and a couple of sheets
of Elvis postage stamps.

332
00:20:28,184 --> 00:20:32,058
Grandma’s spending Christmas
with the superstars

333
00:20:32,125 --> 00:20:35,550
since that reindeer ran her down
that fateful night.

334
00:20:37,105 --> 00:20:41,163
Grandma’s hanging out
with all those late, great stars

335
00:20:41,198 --> 00:20:44,729
for the heavenliest Christmas
of her life.

336
00:20:50,203 --> 00:20:51,943
Okay, I’ll sign.

337
00:20:52,057 --> 00:20:54,294
Oh, this is easier than I thought.

338
00:20:54,682 --> 00:20:57,530
Sign here and here. Initial this.

339
00:20:57,904 --> 00:21:01,244
Oh, and this one gives me power
of attorney over your affairs.

340
00:21:01,283 --> 00:21:04,826
I’ll be your dedicated money manager
forever.

341
00:21:05,533 --> 00:21:06,965
I do feel better.

342
00:21:07,202 --> 00:21:08,097
Perfect!

343
00:21:12,749 --> 00:21:16,250
This is it. The last of grandma’s
fruitcakes from last Christmas.

344
00:21:16,342 --> 00:21:19,850
Oh, do you think it’s still good?
Did she use preservatives?

345
00:21:20,102 --> 00:21:22,646
Preservatives? It’s a fruitcake.

346
00:21:24,426 --> 00:21:26,209
What do we do when it’s sold?

347
00:21:27,850 --> 00:21:28,702
Nothing!

348
00:21:29,640 --> 00:21:31,596
Because we’re going to be rich!

349
00:21:31,801 --> 00:21:33,265
We won the lottery!

350
00:21:33,328 --> 00:21:36,343
– We’re going to be rich?
– We’re going to be rich!

351
00:21:36,381 --> 00:21:37,596
We could retire?

352
00:21:38,063 --> 00:21:39,262
What’s going on?

353
00:21:39,596 --> 00:21:43,432
Our boat’s come in.
Cousin Mel says we won the lottery!

354
00:21:43,887 --> 00:21:46,782
– Won the lottery? All right!
– Sort of.

355
00:21:47,828 --> 00:21:51,735
Actually, I’m going over to see Austin
Bucks and sell this dump for millions.

356
00:21:51,972 --> 00:21:54,798
Thank grandpa.
He gave me power of attorney.

357
00:21:55,924 --> 00:21:56,776
Do what?

358
00:21:57,068 --> 00:21:58,315
Grandpa!

359
00:21:58,648 --> 00:22:00,490
How could you do that?

360
00:22:01,052 --> 00:22:03,003
I thought I was helping.

361
00:22:03,544 --> 00:22:06,579
Talk about having your cake
and eating it, too.

362
00:22:08,542 --> 00:22:09,991
I’ve got to stop her.

363
00:22:37,182 --> 00:22:39,261
Mr. Buck’s office – which way?

364
00:22:44,123 --> 00:22:46,121
Jake! Nice stop.

365
00:22:46,672 --> 00:22:49,469
Please, please don’t buy grandma’s store.

366
00:22:49,686 --> 00:22:54,299
Too late, kid. With this last piece of
property Mr. Bucks will own all of Cityville.

367
00:22:54,701 --> 00:22:55,735
Who are you?

368
00:22:56,238 --> 00:22:58,830
Cousin Mel’s attorney, I. M. Slime.

369
00:22:59,208 --> 00:23:01,106
You said it, not me.

370
00:23:02,607 --> 00:23:03,766
Sorry, Jake.

371
00:23:04,131 --> 00:23:07,167
The only person who can stop this sale
is your grandma but

372
00:23:07,245 --> 00:23:09,227
no one knows what happened to her.

373
00:23:09,243 --> 00:23:11,499
She got run over by Santa’s reindeer.

374
00:23:11,994 --> 00:23:14,274
I just need more time to find grandma.

375
00:23:14,699 --> 00:23:18,093
Now, Austin, darling, why don’t we go
somewhere romantic

376
00:23:18,094 --> 00:23:20,114
and consummate this deal?

377
00:23:23,575 --> 00:23:27,476
You got it, kid. This deal doesn’t
close till the end of the week.

378
00:23:28,220 --> 00:23:29,068
No!

379
00:23:29,444 --> 00:23:32,572
You’re an attorney. Do something!
Sue somebody!

380
00:23:33,280 --> 00:23:34,656
A bit of advice.

381
00:23:34,857 --> 00:23:39,139
If you really believe grandma was run over
by Santa’s reindeer then find him.

382
00:23:39,455 --> 00:23:41,357
He should know where grandma is.

383
00:23:42,266 --> 00:23:43,907
Okay, I will!

384
00:23:49,851 --> 00:23:54,490
I have till the end of the week to stop
cousin Mel from selling grandma’s store.

385
00:23:54,812 --> 00:23:58,066
Look, Sherlock. You’ve tried your best
to find grandma.

386
00:23:58,306 --> 00:24:00,042
Your room is search central.

387
00:24:00,109 --> 00:24:03,129
You got no results from your
do-it-yourself police sketch.

388
00:24:03,521 --> 00:24:06,314
Your dry erase board is full of
dead-end clues.

389
00:24:07,235 --> 00:24:08,573
Give it up.

390
00:24:22,377 --> 00:24:24,850
You’re right, Doofus, we can’t give up.

391
00:24:31,354 --> 00:24:32,383
What’s this?

392
00:24:33,034 --> 00:24:35,020
Printout of my old Christmas list?

393
00:24:35,669 --> 00:24:40,241
Look, Doofus, it’s not as simple as adding
“find grandma” to my Christmas list

394
00:24:40,433 --> 00:24:42,681
and e-mailing it to Santa Claus.

395
00:24:43,223 --> 00:24:43,941
Wait.

396
00:24:45,216 --> 00:24:46,963
Doofus, you’re a genius!

397
00:24:48,113 --> 00:24:52,103
To Santa Claus @SantaClausIsReal.com.

398
00:25:22,312 --> 00:25:24,440
Quincy, you better see this.

399
00:25:31,147 --> 00:25:31,869
None.

400
00:25:32,047 --> 00:25:34,120
Not a single letter from Cityville.

401
00:25:34,400 --> 00:25:37,349
It’s as if they’re too busy
with their prefabricated,

402
00:25:37,536 --> 00:25:40,252
mass-produced lives to need me anymore.

403
00:25:40,374 --> 00:25:41,484
Excuse me.

404
00:25:41,524 --> 00:25:45,717
I might as well shave my beard
and cancel the holidays in Cityville.

405
00:25:46,244 --> 00:25:49,683
If I could meet just one stinking person

406
00:25:49,695 --> 00:25:52,748
who understands the holidays are about
human kindness

407
00:25:52,913 --> 00:25:55,440
with only a touch of conspicuous
consumption.

408
00:25:59,105 --> 00:26:01,174
Yes, Quincy? What’s this?

409
00:26:01,722 --> 00:26:02,880
Careful, Royce.

410
00:26:03,487 --> 00:26:06,409
Donna wanted a doll with braids with
a red ribbon.

411
00:26:06,685 --> 00:26:08,014
She’s on the good list.

412
00:26:11,147 --> 00:26:14,030
The mystery of grandma X is solved.

413
00:26:17,266 --> 00:26:18,966
Grandma Spankenheimer?

414
00:26:19,337 --> 00:26:21,357
Grandma Spankenheimer?

415
00:26:21,562 --> 00:26:22,674
Spankenheimer?

416
00:26:25,201 --> 00:26:28,465
No, never met her. But you might ask
one of those short fellers.

417
00:26:28,483 --> 00:26:31,357
Classic case of amnesia.
Can’t remember a thing.

418
00:26:31,811 --> 00:26:34,558
The Christmas lights are on but
nobody’s home.

419
00:26:35,035 --> 00:26:37,148
E-mail a reply immediately!

420
00:26:40,585 --> 00:26:42,774
I have a better idea.

421
00:27:04,086 --> 00:27:05,502
Call off the hound!

422
00:27:08,219 --> 00:27:09,897
Hi, I’m Quincy,

423
00:27:10,071 --> 00:27:11,110
Santa’s elf.

424
00:27:11,487 --> 00:27:12,942
Top elf, to be exact.

425
00:27:13,252 --> 00:27:15,789
I fly right seat on the sleigh.

426
00:27:16,104 --> 00:27:20,617
The man in the red suit doesn’t make
a move without consulting me first.

427
00:27:20,983 --> 00:27:22,139
You’re an elf.

428
00:27:22,668 --> 00:27:24,147
The genuine article.

429
00:27:29,538 --> 00:27:31,672
What are you doing here in September?

430
00:27:31,971 --> 00:27:33,585
I came to ask a question.

431
00:27:34,127 --> 00:27:36,208
Would you like to find your grandma?

432
00:27:36,418 --> 00:27:39,089
More than all the presents in the world.

433
00:27:39,178 --> 00:27:40,353
Then follow me.

434
00:27:43,345 --> 00:27:46,331
Grandpa, I’m going to the North Pole
to find grandma.

435
00:27:46,666 --> 00:27:48,501
Fine, thanks for telling me.

436
00:28:00,912 --> 00:28:03,397
Old St. Nick and Mrs. Claus

437
00:28:03,654 --> 00:28:05,712
decided just this year:

438
00:28:06,399 --> 00:28:08,237
there won’t be any Christmas –

439
00:28:09,077 --> 00:28:11,212
the feeling’s just not here.

440
00:28:12,022 --> 00:28:14,365
Some kids get more than they need

441
00:28:14,744 --> 00:28:16,711
and some are spoiled rotten.

442
00:28:17,494 --> 00:28:19,819
And when it comes to Christmas time

443
00:28:20,200 --> 00:28:22,551
too many are forgotten.

444
00:28:22,912 --> 00:28:25,800
It will feel like Christmas

445
00:28:25,902 --> 00:28:27,950
to people everywhere,

446
00:28:28,529 --> 00:28:31,194
it will feel like Christmas

447
00:28:31,459 --> 00:28:33,617
when we all learn to share.

448
00:28:34,313 --> 00:28:36,695
Santa said to Mrs. Claus

449
00:28:37,125 --> 00:28:39,232
“Something’s way off track –

450
00:28:39,764 --> 00:28:41,841
I can’t get into Christmas

451
00:28:42,409 --> 00:28:44,575
until the spirit’s back.”

452
00:28:45,500 --> 00:28:48,255
It will feel like Christmas

453
00:28:48,520 --> 00:28:50,551
to people everywhere,

454
00:28:51,042 --> 00:28:53,782
it will feel like Christmas

455
00:28:53,954 --> 00:28:56,458
when we all learn to share.

456
00:29:02,671 --> 00:29:06,441
You better have a good reason
why you broke elf code

457
00:29:06,652 --> 00:29:08,486
and brought a human here.

458
00:29:09,033 --> 00:29:11,699
Thought you’d like to meet
Jake Spankenheimer.

459
00:29:12,240 --> 00:29:15,195
The Jake Spankenheimer who loves
rollerblades,

460
00:29:15,258 --> 00:29:17,564
video games, pillow fights
with his sister,

461
00:29:17,643 --> 00:29:21,189
procrastinates once in a while with his
homework – not that I condone it –,

462
00:29:21,209 --> 00:29:25,513
writes to me every Christmas
and helps his grandma in the kitchen?

463
00:29:25,902 --> 00:29:30,736
It’s nice to finally meet someone from
Cityville who still believes in me.

464
00:29:31,395 --> 00:29:33,144
Pretty cool.

465
00:29:33,391 --> 00:29:36,190
Which is why you’re not sweeping up
reindeer chips.

466
00:29:39,365 --> 00:29:42,381
Grandma, there’s someone here
who wants to see you.

467
00:29:44,294 --> 00:29:45,303
Grandma!

468
00:29:51,631 --> 00:29:53,201
Okay, I’ll bite. Who is he?

469
00:29:56,013 --> 00:29:58,423
It’s me, Jake.  Don’t you remember?

470
00:30:00,642 --> 00:30:01,818
No, nothin’.

471
00:30:02,368 --> 00:30:03,086
Wait…

472
00:30:04,514 --> 00:30:06,607
No. Thought I had somethin’.

473
00:30:07,211 --> 00:30:08,719
You’ve got to remember.

474
00:30:08,947 --> 00:30:10,539
Cousin Mel’s taking over.

475
00:30:10,693 --> 00:30:11,949
Who’s cousin Mel?

476
00:30:12,580 --> 00:30:15,790
You know, big red hair, greedy,
moneygrubbing,

477
00:30:15,835 --> 00:30:18,649
too much jewelry, beats grandpa at cards.

478
00:30:18,675 --> 00:30:20,505
She doesn’t sound very nice.

479
00:30:21,144 --> 00:30:22,081
She isn’t.

480
00:30:22,482 --> 00:30:26,689
If you don’t come back right away she’s
going to sell your store to Mr. Bucks.

481
00:30:27,188 --> 00:30:30,920
Without it, our family and Christmas
will never be the same.

482
00:30:31,263 --> 00:30:32,600
That’s terrible.

483
00:30:33,330 --> 00:30:34,616
Who are you again?

484
00:30:35,703 --> 00:30:38,010
Will you come back with me
and stop the sale?

485
00:30:38,428 --> 00:30:41,134
Better than laying around here all day
getting fat.

486
00:30:41,340 --> 00:30:42,598
Oh, yeah!

487
00:30:42,965 --> 00:30:45,340
Quincy, hook up the reindeer to the sleigh.

488
00:30:45,658 --> 00:30:47,279
We’re headed to the city.

489
00:30:54,713 --> 00:30:55,650
Turn here.

490
00:30:57,435 --> 00:30:58,941
We’re here!

491
00:30:59,356 --> 00:31:00,724
Better park in back.

492
00:31:02,514 --> 00:31:04,870
Cousin Mel wasn’t about
to give up easily.

493
00:31:05,953 --> 00:31:09,443
I remember what happened next.
It was a warm, September day.

494
00:31:14,516 --> 00:31:15,927
That was a landin’.

495
00:31:16,318 --> 00:31:19,796
